Part 5: index.html vs index.jsp - The Real Difference
index.html (Static)
When to use: Landing page, login page, about page

Contains: Pure HTML and CSS

Cannot: Show data from database, use Java variables

Speed: Fastest

Example index.html:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Employee Management</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="bootstrap.min.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to Employee Management System</h1>
    <p>This text is the SAME for every user, every time.</p>
    
    <a href="login.html" class="btn btn-primary">Login</a>
    <a href="register.html" class="btn btn-secondary">Register</a>
</body>
</html>
index.jsp (Dynamic)
When to use: Dashboard, homepage with user-specific data

Contains: HTML + small amounts of Java

Can: Show database data, use session variables

Speed: Slower (server must compile)

Example index.jsp:

jsp
<%@ page import="com.Model.Employee" %>
<%@ page import="java.util.List" %>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Dashboard</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="bootstrap.min.css">
</head>
<body>
    <%
        // Get logged-in user from session
        String userName = (String) session.getAttribute("username");
        
        if(userName != null) {
            // User IS logged in
    %>
        <h1>Welcome back, <%= userName %>!</h1>
        <p>Today's date: <%= new java.util.Date() %></p>
        <a href="EmployeeServlet?action=list">View Employees</a>
        <a href="logout.jsp">Logout</a>
        
    <% } else { 
            // User is NOT logged in
    %>
        <h1>Welcome, Guest!</h1>
        <p>Please <a href="login.html">login</a> to access the system.</p>
        
    <% } %>
</body>
</html>
Key Difference:

index.html shows the SAME to everyone

index.jsp can show DIFFERENT content based on who's viewing

