Part 8: Simple Rules to Remember
The Golden Rules:
JSP never talks to database - always through Controller and DAO

Servlet never writes HTML - forwards to JSP for display

DAO never knows about web - no request/response objects

Bean is just a backpack - carries data, does nothing else

The Flow Pattern (Always the Same):
text
1. User clicks something in JSP
2. Request goes to Servlet (Controller)
3. Servlet creates/uses Bean
4. Servlet calls DAO
5. DAO talks to Database
6. DAO returns data to Servlet
7. Servlet forwards to JSP
8. JSP displays data to user
File Extension Meanings:
.html = Static page (no Java, no database)

.jsp = Dynamic page (can show Java data)

.java = Java code (Bean, DAO, Servlet)

Part 9: Common Questions from Beginners
Q: Can I put database code directly in JSP?
A: Yes, but DON'T. It's bad practice. Use MVC.

Q: Why do I need a Bean? Can't I just pass variables?
A: Bean groups related data. Passing 10 variables is messy. Passing 1 Bean is clean.

Q: What if I have 20 database tables?
A: You'll have 20 Beans and 20 DAOs. One for each table.

Q: Can JSP call DAO directly?
A: Technically yes, but that breaks MVC. Always go through Servlet.

Q: What's the difference between forward and redirect?
A:

forward = Server internally goes to JSP (URL stays same)

redirect = Server tells browser to go somewhere else (URL changes)

